            <div type="emblem" n="e30"><!-- Change the value of n to "e" followed by the number of the emblem. Use two digits for all numbers. -->
                <pb n="95"/><!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                
                
                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 30. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>Luna is as requisite to Sol as a <choice><orig>henne</orig> to a <choice><orig>cocke</orig>.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 30.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>What can you <choice><orig>doe</orig> dear Sol! alone, if I</l>
                        <l><orig>Joyne</orig> not as <choice><orig>henne</orig> with <choice><orig>cocke</orig> to multiply?</l>
                        <l>Or can I Luna Natures <choice><orig>guifts</orig><reg>gifts</reg></choice> <choice><orig>expresse</orig><reg>express</reg></choice></l>
                        <l>Without your <choice><orig>ayde</orig><reg>aid</reg></choice>? <choice><orig>noe</orig>, grant <choice><orig>mee</orig> some <choice><orig>redresse</orig>.</l>
                        <l><orig>Hee</orig>'s but a <choice><orig>foole</orig><reg>fool</reg></choice> those to confine apart</l>
                        <l><orig>Whome</orig> Nature would have <choice><orig>joynd</orig> in mind and heart.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="96"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 30.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>Avicenne in his <choice><orig>booke</orig> of the <choice><orig>Soule</orig> <choice><orig>divers</orig> times <choice><orig>admonisheth</orig><reg>admonishes</reg></choice>, that <choice><orig>noe</orig><pc>-</pc><milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>eggs are to be taken for art, but <choice><orig>onely</orig> of those <choice><orig>henns</orig>, which had a cock:
                        <lb/>that is, the <choice><orig>fæminine</orig><reg>feminine</reg></choice> subject <choice><orig>avayles</orig> nothing without the masculine<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>virtue, and on the contrary, nor a <choice><orig>cocke</orig> profitable without a <choice><orig>henne</orig>:
                        <lb/>for both these sexes must be <choice><orig>joynd</orig> together in the <choice><orig>Philosophicall</orig> <choice><orig>coupe</orig><reg>coop</reg></choice>,
                        <lb/>that multiplication may be made: The Philosophers <choice><orig>doe</orig> indeed use
                        <lb/>the similitude taken from a <choice><orig>cocke</orig>, because in the first place <choice><orig>hee</orig> is<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>more correspondent to the power of Sulphur, than any other male of
                        <lb/>birds, one being able to serve many <choice><orig>henns</orig>, and not easily suffering a
                        <lb/><choice><orig>rivall</orig><reg>rival</reg></choice> in the same dunghill, thinking <choice><orig>himselfe</orig> convenient and suffi
                        <lb break="no"/>cient for everyone. <choice><orig>Hee</orig> is the bird of Mars, <choice><orig>transformd</orig><reg>transformed</reg></choice>, as the Poets
                        <lb/>fable, from the youth Gallus, who was entrusted to observe Sol, that<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>hee</orig> might not discover the adultery of Mars with Venus, and very
                        <lb/><choice><orig>Martiall</orig><reg>Martial</reg></choice> in fight, contending with his adversary even to death: In<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the <choice><orig>Philosophicall</orig> <choice><orig>worke</orig> <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>repræsents</orig> Sol, as the <choice><orig>henne</orig> <choice><orig>doth</orig> Luna:
                        <lb/>there is therefore the same necessity of <choice><orig>joyning</orig> Sol with Luna, as a<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>cocke</orig> with a <choice><orig>henne</orig>: The <choice><orig>cocke</orig> is <choice><orig>allso</orig> consecrated to Sol, at whose<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>approach <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>riseth</orig><reg>rises</reg></choice>, and goes to sleep with him: <choice><orig>hee</orig> often looks up to<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>heaven, and erects his hooked <choice><orig>tayle</orig> upright: <choice><orig>hee</orig> fights against Serpents in
                        <lb/><choice><orig>defence</orig><reg>defense</reg></choice> of his <choice><orig>henns</orig>: <choice><orig>hee</orig> is an acceptable messenger of light and Latona<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>being <choice><orig>præsent</orig> at her <choice><orig>labour</orig>: Latona indeed brought forth Sol and Luna,
                        <lb/>and therefore <choice><orig>hee</orig> is appropriated to the mother and <choice><orig>Sonne</orig>: But Sol,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Luna, and Latona <choice><orig>doe</orig> in <choice><orig>Chymicall</orig> subjects agree, <choice><orig>soe</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> the <choice><orig>cocke</orig>
                        <lb/>and <choice><orig>henne</orig>: but these <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>proceded</orig> from an <choice><orig>egge</orig>, and <choice><orig>againe</orig> <choice><orig>doe</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>lay eggs for the production of young chickens; <choice><orig>soe</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>doe</orig> the Philoso
                        <lb break="no"/>phers eggs <choice><orig>turne</orig> into birds of the same kind, provided they be kept<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>warme</orig> with temperate heat, as is the heat of a brooding <choice><orig>henne</orig>, which
                        <lb/>endures continually: For whereas amongst other birds the male <choice><orig>allso</orig>
                        <lb/><orig>sitts</orig> upon the eggs, the <choice><orig>cocke</orig> alone <choice><orig>shews</orig> <choice><orig>himselfe</orig> free from this
                        <lb/>office or <choice><orig>burthen</orig><reg>burden</reg></choice>; and therefore all the care and pains of hatching the
                        <lb/>eggs, and producing chickens <choice><orig>lyes</orig> upon the <choice><orig>henne</orig>; where her sedulity
                        <lb/>and diligence may be observed, how hastily <choice><orig>Shee</orig> eats and drinks, and
                        <lb/>unloads her belly, and presently <choice><orig>runns</orig> <choice><orig>backe</orig> to her eggs, before they be<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>cold: Then with what force and violence <choice><orig>Shee</orig> defends her chickens,
                        <lb/>with what <choice><orig>tendernesse</orig><reg>tenderness</reg></choice> <choice><orig>Shee</orig> receives and covers them being naked under
                        <lb/>her wings, with what a <choice><orig>voyce</orig>, as with a bell, <choice><orig>Shee</orig> calls and keeps them<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>together, with what study <choice><orig>Shee</orig> breaks the harder crums or seeds for<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>them, and <choice><orig>præsents</orig> them with her <choice><orig>beake</orig>, as on a knife, this <choice><orig>worke</orig> of<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>nature is worthy of admiration. And all these things are, that man
                        <lb/>may neither want eggs nor chickens for aliment: After the same man
                        <lb break="no"/>ner the Philosopher or artist <choice><orig>doth</orig> most diligently and providently<pc>-</pc>
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="97"/><fw>Discourse 30.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>proceed in all his operations; For <choice><orig>hee</orig> picks up eggs there where a <choice><orig>cocke</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>hath</orig> been, trying them whether they be adle, after that <choice><orig>hee</orig> <choice><orig>cleanseth</orig><reg>cleanses</reg></choice><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>præpares</orig>, and <choice><orig>disposseth</orig><reg>disposses</reg></choice> them in his <choice><orig>vessells</orig>, as nests, and administers due
                        <lb/>heat, whereby the subjects <choice><orig>mixd</orig> together daily act and suffer one by<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>another, till after a long time passing through various <choice><orig>colours</orig> they come
                        <lb/>to one <choice><orig>colour</orig> and <choice><orig>essence</orig><reg>essense</reg></choice>: In which operation Solution, congulation,
                        <lb/>Sublimation, ascension, descension, distillation, calcination and fixion
                        <lb/>as intermediate are perfected: for a hard and compact thing cannot<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>be altered, therefore Solution is <choice><orig>præmised</orig>, that is may be made liquid
                        <lb/>and soft: and where a thing is dissolved, it is convenient <choice><orig>allso</orig> to be<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>coagulated, not to its former <choice><orig>hardnesse</orig> but a <choice><orig>honyish</orig><reg>honeyish</reg></choice> tractability;<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Sublimation separates the pure from the impure, and makes a thing
                        <lb/>vile more worthy, the <choice><orig>inferiour</orig> <choice><orig>superiour</orig>; and therefore this nei
                        <lb break="no"/>ther ought to be wanting, for it is as the <choice><orig>mistresse</orig> and <choice><orig>directresse</orig><reg>directness</reg></choice><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>of all: when sublimation is made, some parts ascend higher, which
                        <lb/>is ascension, and others <choice><orig>againe</orig> descend, and <choice><orig>soe</orig> descension is made:
                        <lb/>Distillation <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>clarifyes</orig> the whole being often interposed, and that
                        <lb/>which <choice><orig>remaynes</orig> in the <choice><orig>bottome</orig> is calcined: then both are fixed, and
                        <lb/><orig>soe</orig> the <choice><orig>worke</orig> is completed. But if a man gather all these parti
                        <lb break="no"/>cular operations under a <choice><orig>generall</orig>, which is Coction, <choice><orig>hee</orig> will not<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><choice><orig>erre</orig><reg>err</reg></choice> much from the purpose: for as <choice><orig>soe</orig> many chickens as there are,
                        <lb/>which <choice><orig>runne</orig> here and there dispersedly, <choice><orig>doe</orig> resort to one mother or
                        <lb/><orig>nurce</orig> the <choice><orig>henne</orig>, <choice><orig>soe</orig> <choice><orig>doe</orig> <choice><orig>soe</orig> many <choice><orig>severall</orig> <choice><orig>wayes</orig> of operating <choice><orig>con
                        <lb break="no"/>curre</orig> to the womans <choice><orig>worke</orig>, that is, coction alone: It is Luna, which<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>comes to be exalted to the sublimity of Sol, for whose sake all these
                        <lb/>things are done, that is, durable matrimony is intended between Sol<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and Luna, which if effected, all legations, desponsations, copulations,
                        <lb/>dubitatious, ct.<!-- not sure about this abbreviation --> will cease. and the bed and flesh of both will be one,
                        <lb/><orig>mutuall</orig> and constant love, <choice><orig>æternall</orig> peace, and an indissoluble alli
                        <lb break="no"/>ance: Sol without Luna is of <choice><orig>noe</orig> great <choice><orig>esteeme</orig>, and Luna without
                        <lb/>Sol of <choice><orig>meane</orig> and sordid condition: But <choice><orig>Shee</orig> receives <choice><orig>splendour</orig>, and
                        <lb/>dignity, with strength or constancy of mind and body from Sol her<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>husband, and Sol from Luna multiplication of offspring, and pro
                        <lb break="no"/>pagation of kind: hereupon <choice><orig>Sayth</orig> the Rosary: If <choice><orig>onely</orig> one of them<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Should be in our stone, the medicine would never flow easily, nor,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>yeild</orig> the tincture, and if it should <choice><orig>yeild</orig>, it would not tinge, <choice><orig>unlesse</orig>
                        <lb/>for see much as <choice><orig>allso</orig> the remainder would be, and the Mercury would
                        <lb/>evaporate in fume, because the receptacle of the tincture would not
                        <lb/>be in it: And Geber in his <choice><orig>booke</orig> of examinations proves, that if Sol<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and Luna be incorporated together with art, they are not easily<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>separated<pc>. . . . . . . . . . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
            </div>
